'''Joe Rice''' (born [[May 7]] [[1967]]<ref name="votesmart">{{cite web |url=http://www.vote-smart.org/bio.php?can_id=65119 |title=Representative Joe Rice |accessdate=2008-01-11 |format=html |work=Project Vote Smart}}</ref>) is a legislator in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. A [[U.S. Army]] and [[Iraq War]] veteran, and former mayor of the City of [[Glendale, Colorado|Glendale]], Rice won election to the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]] in 2006. He represents House District 38, which encompasses [[Greenwood Village, Colorado|Greenwood Village]], [[Bow Mar, Colorado|Bow Mar]], and [[Littleton, Colorado]] as well as parts of [[Englewood, Colorado|Englewood]], [[Centennial, Colorado|Centennial]], [[Aurora, Colorado|Aurora]], and [[Columbine Valley, Colorado|Columbine Valley]].<ref name="map">{{cite web |url=http://comaps.org/district38h.html |title=State House District 38 |accessdate=2008-01-11 |format=html |work=COMaps }}</ref> 

==Biography==

===Military career===

Born in [[New Castle, Indiana]],<ref name="votesmart"/> Rice enlisted in the [[United States Army]] at the age of 17,<ref name="rocky">{{cite web |url=http://cfapp2.rockymountainnews.com/election/profiles/c_profiles.cfm?oper=cand_profile&id=11984&qa=1 |title=Joe Rice - Colorado - State House District 38 candidate |accessdate=2008-01-11 |format=html |work=RockyMountainNews.com }}</ref> and spent three years on active duty as an Airborne Ranger Infantry Officer. His military service included duty in [[Bosnia-Herzegovina]] as a staff officer during UN peacekeeping operations, and as project officer for a [[Colorado National Guard]] program to provide medical care to poor civilians. He remains a member of the [[United States Army Reserve]].<ref name="mil">{{cite web |url=http://www.joericecolorado.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=14&Itemid=30 |title=Joe's Military Service |accessdate=2008-01-11 |work=Citizens for Joe Rice }}</ref>

Presently a [[lieutenant colonel]] in the [[United States Army Reserve]], Rice has been called up to serve three tours of duty in [[Iraq]] &mdash; from March 2003 to May 2004, where he was the senior U.S. military advisor to the [[Baghdad]] City Council; from October 2005 to February 2006, where he advised coalition forces on interactions with Iraqi civilians; and his current tour, where from October 2007 to January 2008, where, as an operations analyst, he is evaluating Iraqi military and police forces.<ref name="mil"/><ref name="headed">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=State Rep. Joe Rice headed for Iraq |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7005085
|work=Denver Post |date=[[26 September]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> [[Airborne]] and [[U.S. Army Ranger|Ranger]] qualified, Rice has received the [[Combat Action Badge]], the [[Expert Infantryman<U+2019>s Badge]], and the [[Bronze Star]].<ref name="rocky"/> Building upon his work in Baghdad, Rice has also helped coordinate the Baghdad-Denver Region Partnership for [[Sister Cities International]] since 2004.<ref name="votesmart"/> The partnership brought several delegations of Iraqis including business leaders, government officials, and scholars.  The most recent delegation was comprised of Iraqi teenagers who lived with Colorado families.<ref name="revel">{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Martin |title=Iraqi youths revel in Colorado |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_6503343
|work=Denver Post |date=[[31 July]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

===Private sector career===

Rice earned an [[associates degree]] from [[New Mexico Military Institute]] in 1987, a bachelor's degree in [[history]] from [[Metropolitan State College of Denver]] in 1989,<ref name="votesmart"/> and a [[Masters of Public Administration]] from the [[University of Colorado]].<ref name="rocky"/> Rice is married; he and his wife, Kendall, have three children &mdash; twins Harrison and Alexandria, and a younger son, Dalton.<ref name="bio"/> After being discharged from active duty at [[Fort Carson, Colorado]], Rice settled in [[Glendale, Colorado]] in 1990.<ref name="party">{{cite news |first=Justin |last=Berton |title=The Glendale T&A Party |url=http://www.westword.com/2000-01-20/news/the-glendale-t-a-party/
|work=Westword |date=[[20 January]] [[2000]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

While in the Army Reserve, Rice spent ten years in the private sector as a customer service supervisor and trainer with [[MCI]], [[JDEdwards]], and [[Wells Fargo Bank]], and as worked as a management consultant.<ref name="bio">{{cite web |url=http://www.joericecolorado.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=16&Itemid=33 |title=About Joe |accessdate=2008-01-11 |work=Citizens for Joe Rice }}</ref> 

From 1993 to 1995, Rice was the manager of Dismas House, a [[halfway home]] for ex-convicts. In his first legislative campaign, Rice was criticized for his association with Dismas House founder Bob Sylvester, who was found guilty in 2000 of sexually abusing inmates. The incidents for which Sylvester was tried occurred after Rice left his employment at Dismas, and Rice testified on behalf of the prosecution during Sylvester's trial.<ref name="dismas">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Blake: Roy can't give up politics |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/opinion_columnists/article/0,2777,DRMN_23972_5108165,00.html
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[1 November]] [[2006]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

===Mayor of Glendale===

In 1994, Rice was elected to the Glendale, Colorado city council,<ref name="votesmart"/> running on a platform of shifting the small Denver enclave's business base away from adult-oriented businesses and towards a more "resident-family community." He was elected mayor in 1996. During his first term, Rice proposed new regulations on [[erotic dancers]] at Glendale nightclubs, garnering strong opposition from local business owners, who formed the "Glendale Tea Party" and successfully elected three members to the city council in 1998 in response to the new regulations.<ref name="party"/> Running for re-election, Rice faced opposition from Tea Party member Mike Dunafon in a race that saw uncharacteristically negative campaigning for Glendale, including accusations that Rice used racial slurs and denigrated [[African-American]] and [[Mexican]] citizens.<ref name="doggone">{{cite news |first=Justin |last=Berton |title=That Doggone Glendale |url=http://www.westword.com/2000-03-02/news/that-doggone-glendale/
|work=Westword |date=[[2 March]] [[2000]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> Rice was also criticized for being absent from Glendale during six months of his term as mayor, while he attended U.S. Army National Guard command school at Fort Leavenworth.<ref name="party"/> However after an election that saw record campaign spending and record turnout for Glendale, Rice defeated Dunafon and was re-elected to a second term in 2000.<ref name="shame">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Hall of Shame |url=http://westword.com/2000-12-28/news/hall-of-shame/full
|work=Westword |date=[[28 December]] [[2000]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

As mayor, Rice touted his efforts to lower city property taxes, expand city parks and open space, and open the city's first first pre-school and recreation center.<ref name="rocky"/><ref name="mayor">{{cite web |url=http://www.joericecolorado.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=15&Itemid=31 |title=Joe as Mayor of Glendale |accessdate=2008-01-11 |work=Citizens for Joe Rice }}</ref> He served on the executive committee of the Denver Regional Council of Governments from 1995 to 2003, as vice-chair of the [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]] Metro Mayors Caucus from 2001 to 2003,<ref name="votesmart"/> and received the John V. Christensen Award from the Denver Regional Council of Governments in 2004. In 2003, Rice resigned from his post as mayor during the last year of his second term after being called up to active military duty in [[Iraq]].<ref name="mayor"/>

