===2006 election===

Republican [[Joe Stengel]] was [[term-limit]]ed in 2006 and could not stand for re-election; both Rice and Republican Matt Dunn sought the seat.<ref name="regain">{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Ewegen |title=GOP fights to regain Colorado House |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_4524830
|work=Denver Post |date=[[20 October]] [[2006]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> Rice was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]''<ref name="endorsed">{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Weighing Colorado legislative candidates |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_4448950
|work=Denver Post |date=[[8 October]] [[2006]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> and won with 53 percent of the vote.<ref name="map"/> The race was a top target for the Colorado GOP, who unsuccessfully tried to keep the seat in Republican hands during a year where Republicans lost ground both nationally and in Colorado.<ref name="defense">{{cite news |first=Lynn |last=Bartels |title=Dems find selves in rare defense mode |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/elections/article/0,2808,DRMN_24736_4903629,00.html
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[9 August]] [[2006]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

During the campaign, Rice was criticized in [[attack ad]]s for his support, as mayor of Glendale, of the use of [[Mexico|Mexican]]-issed ''[[matricula consular]]'' cards as legal forms of identification for use by immigrants.<ref name="soft">{{cite news |first=Fernando |last=Quintero |title=Rice rips ads saying he's 'soft' on illegals |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/elections/article/0,2808,DRMN_24736_5088664,00.html
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[24 October]] [[2006]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref><ref name="matrica">{{cite news |first=Fernando |last=Quintero |title=Mexican ID cards caught in politics |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/elections/article/0,2808,DRMN_24736_5097494,00.html
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[27 October]] [[2006]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

===2007 legislative session===

In the 2007-2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Rice was Vice-Chairman of the House Business Affairs and Labor Committee and a member of the House Transportation and Energy Committee.<ref name="cmtes">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2007-12-11 |format=html |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>

During the 2007 legislative session, Rice sponsored 16 pieces of legislation, including 11 as the primary sponsor in the House of Representatives. Among the most prominent of his successful bills were measures to:
* set up a [[cold case]] unit within the [[Colorado Bureau of Investigation]]<ref name="colddeath">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Cold-case pursuits vs. death penalty |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_6126073
|work=Denver Post |date=[[13 June]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> to investigate Colorado's 1200 unsolved homicides.<ref name="dome222">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Under the dome, 2/22 |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5277303
|work=Denver Post |date=[[21 February]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>
* cut taxes for businesses by raising the personal property tax exemption.<ref name="taxcut">{{cite news |first=Will |last=Shanley |title=Small firms' tax cut on tap |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_5429443
|work=Denver Post |date=[[14 March]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

Rice was also the house sponsor of legislation introduced in the [[Colorado State Senate]] to make driving without a [[seat belt]] a primary offense.<ref name="seat">{{cite news |first=April M. |last=Washington |title=Seat-belt crackdown sought |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/government/article/0,2777,DRMN_23906_5322556,00.html
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[2 February]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

===2008 legislative session===

Rice was serving his third tour of duty in Iraq at the start of the 2008 legislative session; his presence was acknowledged by lawmakers during their opening speeches,<ref name="groff">{{cite news |first=Colleen |last=Slevin |title=Peter Groff elected first black president of Colorado Senate |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7922659
|work=Denver Post |date=[[9 January]] [[2008]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> his seat was decorated with [[yellow ribbon]]s, and his children were invited to lead the [[Pledge of Allegiance]].<ref name="curtain">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Curtain rises on 2008 legislature |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7926208
|work=Denver Post |date=[[10 January]] [[2008]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> During his time in Iraq, Rice met with Colorado Governor [[Bill Ritter]], Congressman [[Ed Perlmutter]], and Congressional candidate [[Jared Polis]] during their trips to the country,<ref name="ritter">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Ritter trip to Iraq a secret |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7704988
|work=Denver Post |date=[[13 December]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref><ref name="perl">{{cite news |first=Anne C. |last=Mulkern |title=Perlmutter heading to Iraq |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7581932
|work=Denver Post |date=[[28 November]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref><ref name="polis">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |title=Polis takes to Web with observations on journey to Iraq |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2007/nov/22/polis-takes-to-web-with-observations-on-journey/
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[22 November]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> and also met with U.S. Marine and Colorado state senator [[Steve Ward]], who was stationed in Iraq at the same time.<ref name="tour">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Littleton legislator heads to Iraq for 3rd tour of duty as Army officer |url=http://www.denverpost.com//ci_7252953
|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=[[31 October]] [[2007]] |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref>

In the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Rice sits on the House Transportation and Energy Committee, and is vice-chairman of the House Business Affairs and Labor Committee.
<ref name="cmte2008">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-19 |format=html |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>

